ocr.sentence: matter the king was very glad hereof, and caused the combatants to be brought before him, to whom he said gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversie shall be ended that is now amongst you Are you contented to stand to his iudg-ment that I shall appoint they all answered, that they were.
ocr.region: OF FRYER BACON. 221 the matter the kingwas very glad hereof,and caused the combatants to be brought before him, to whom he said gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversie shall be ended that is now amongst you Are you contented to stand to his iudg ment that I shaU appoint they all answered, that they were. Then were they bid to returne three days after. In that time Fryer Bacon had caused the body of their deceased father to be taken out of the ground, and brought to the court the body hee did cause to be bound to a stake, naked to the middle upwards and Hkewise prepared three bowes and shafts for the three brethren all these kept hee secretly. The third day being come, came these three brethren, to whom Fryer Bacon in the presence of the king gave the three bowes and shafts, saying, be not offended at what I have done, there is no other way but this to judge your cause See here is the body of your dead father, shoot at him, for he that cometh nearest to his heart, shad have aU the lands and goods. The two eldest prepared themselves, and shot at him, and stucke their arrowes in his breast. Then bid they the youngest to shoot but he refused it, saying, I will rather loose aU, then wound that body that I so loved living Had you ever had but halfe that love in you to him that I have, you would rather have had your own bodies mangled, than to suffer his lifelesse corps thus to be used nay, you doe not onely suffer it, but you are the actors of this act of shame and speaking this, he wept.

ocr.sentence: his master had great marvaile then they sate downe to breakfast, which being ended they went home, and did such thinges as were there to bee done when his dame sawe that he had so soone ended his busines, she thought that he was a profitable servant, and said little but let him alone.
ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 295 whereat his master had great marvade then they sate downe to breakfast, which being ended they went home, and did such thinges as were there to bee done when his dame sawe that he had so soone ended his busines, she thought that he was a profitable servant, and said Httle but let him alone. In the evening Rush de maunded of his master what hee should doe the next morrow ? his master appointed him twice so much as hee did the day before, which Rush refused not, but got up earely in the morning, and went to the field, and about his worke so soone as his master was ready, he tooke his man's breakfast and came to the field, thinking to helpe Rush but he was no sooner come from his house but the Priest came to see his wife, and presently shee made ready some good meate for them to be merry withall, and whyle it was a dressing, they sate sporting together, who had beene there should have seene many loving touches. And when the goodman came to the field, he found that Rush had done aU that which he appointed, whereof he had great marvade then they sate dovroe to breakfast, and as they sate together, Rush beheld his master's shoone, and perceived that for fault of greasing they were very hard then said Rush to his master, why are not your shooes better greased ? I marvade that you can goe in them, they be so hard, have you no more at home ? Ves, said his master, I have another payre lying under a great chest at home in my chamber. Then said Rush I wdl goe home and grease them that you may put them on to-morrow and

And when the goodman came to the field, he found that Rush had done aU that which he appointed, whereof he had great marvade then they sate dovroe to breakfast, and as they sate together, Rush beheld his master's shoone, and perceived that for fault of greasing they were very hard then said Rush to his master, why are not your shooes better greased? I marvade that you can goe in them, they be so hard, have you no more at home? Ves, said his master, I have another payre lying under a great chest at home in my chamber. Then said Rush I wdl goe home and grease them that you may put them on to-morrow and so wente he home, and his wife made haste to put in the things which he had taken out of the Chest. When his master came he found Rush businesse to grease his shoe, and he said to him, how do you, Rush? I doe it with great marvade, the shooes be so hard, they cannot be greased. Then his master seide I will goe home and grease you, and so Rush wente withall, and his master was come, and told him that his shooes were greased, and the shoes being on, he made him put them to a roasting fire, and then he went home, and had great marvade all the day, and in the evening, he found his dame in the mead to sit and dine with some of her friends, so he sat downe to the table, and Rush sawe that his master was well pleased with his businesse.</s>

Quand je relevai la tte, l'obscurit la plus complte salait faite dans votre logement, et une lueur d'espoir tra-, versa mon esprit. Point de doute vous alliez venir, vous alliez paratre. Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

Je vous laisse donc entendre qu'il tait un hros de paille, un enfant qui l'aurait fait. Il l'aurait vu comme un chien qui allait vite dans une chevelure qu'il prfrait, et que ses mains avaient saisi. Je ne me serai jamais prcipite, si quelque chose venait venir de l'intrieur. Il n'est jamais trop tard pour repenser la vie, et avec vous, Ludovic, je me suis dit qu'on pourrait aller  la maison avec le vent au-dessus, jouer au petit chasseur, l'ouvrir en chape

Quand je relevai la tte, l'obscurit la plus complte s'tait faite dans votre logement, et une lueur d'espoir tra-versa mon esprit. Point de doute vous alliez venir, vous alliez paratre. Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez donc en chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. -Ah ! enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous ? A quel titre se prsentait-il ! tait-ce de votre part ? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire ? A tout prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y taient accroch. Il ne me revint jamais au coeur, mais il tait si prs que quelqu'un ne m'avait jamais cach de ses yeux. A -tout ce qui me prsentait  l'esprit le mystre de l'intimit et de l'clat qu'il tait de son ct, j'avais fait une premire impression. - Aucune ruse n'avait t ncessaire, mais c'est au fond ce qu'elle est. Pour arriver  me rencontrer, cet homme n'tait pas sans son petit sourire, c'est--dire qu'il s'en est servi toute la journe pour faire rire d'elle  peine. Comme nous avions l'habitude de le voir, nous ne pensons mme pas  le savoir. A l'image de la rue, le nom de son mtier, le temps que je n'allie jamais les rues, et l'attrait que j'ai pour lui, vous comprendrez, qu'il est impossible d'imaginer son existence sous une telle forme, et  la lumire du mien. De ce point de vue, l'clairage qui pouvait y tre apport ne m'a pas apport une seule clef sur lui. C'est, pour moi, l'ide que je fus crit dans un rve et que, sous le rel, il n'existe pas. - N'empche, Ludovic, il tait un homme quand je l'ai vu, et toutes les ides qu'on m'avait entrepris sur la faon dont il m'envisageait sont encore prsentes. - Nous avons donc bien fait, Ludovic, je vous remercie de m'avoir mis dans le monde et de m'avoir laiss vivre. Je vous laisse donc entendre qu'il tait un hros de paille, un enfant qui l'aurait fait. Il l'aurait vu comme un chien qui allait vite dans une chevelure qu'il prfrait, et que ses mains avaient saisi. Je ne me serai jamais prcipite, si quelque chose venait venir de l'intrieur. Il n'est jamais trop tard pour repenser la vie, et avec vous, Ludovic, je me suis dit qu'on pourrait aller  la maison avec le vent au-dessus, jouer au petit chasseur, l'ouvrir en chape

C'tait au sein d'un monde crmis  l'ombre, au sein d'un pays o la vrit n'tait pas reconnue, o la religion ne prenait qu'un lger place dans la conscience des gens, o le dtournement dans l'entreprise de la justice et de l'ordre tait devenu une vritable science. Marguerite tait en tat de tre mise  mort. Elle tait mre d'un garon. Son fils, petit, d'abord, et s'appelant le garon du roi, avait t chang  une voisine de Marguerite pour le rembourser. En tant que prte-niece de Marguerite, la jeune femme ne voyait jamais son fils; lorsqu'on le laissa aller aux soins dans le chambre d'une maison en bord de mer, c'tait  la sortie du corps qu'on lui demandait s'il venait bien, pourquoi il n'avait pas t le temps d'appuyer sur le bouton de l'ouvrage ; la voiture qui le transportait n'tait pas une vritable voiture, mais plutt une nageuse qui tait en possession d'un mou-nant. Enfin, quand Marguerite tait en paix, elle allait au chteau et cette nuit elle avec de nombreuses autres femmes quittaient le monde.

The foregoing are only some of the legends of Saint Marguerite, some of which are certainly false, and that some of those which are true are too fabulous to be believed. But this legend of her prayer to the Blessed Virgin is so remarkable, that it must be regarded as founded on truth.

The following is a copy of an interesting letter addressed by the writer, Mgr. Jean-Baptiste d'Agoult, to the Society of Jesus, in reply to their request of a copy of the treatise of the Abb de La Vigerie, which they are about to publish, and to which M. d'Agoult had referred. In his letter the Mgr. de La Vigerie says that Mgr. de L'Auray, the author of the "Etude d'un Souverain," had written to him, requesting him to correct his errors, in which he does not appear to have acted very amicably, but that he had agreed, on the occasion of a later discussion, to the correction of a few points, and to the addition of a few paragraphs. But, as the original manuscript, which had been prepared for the Society of Jesus by Mgr. de L'Auray, had been lost, M. d'Agoult says that he could not add to it, and had only been able to correct errors, and to add a few paragraphs, without making any alterations in the spirit or style of the original. The Abb de L'Auray is, therefore, obliged to publish the original manuscript as originally prepared by M. d'Auray, because he cannot do better. 1

Dans l'acte qui instituait le jeune avocat pour son hritier, ces divers voeux taient exprims dans la forme la plus simple et la plus touchante. Elle s'excusait d'avoir si peu  offrir, et priait qu'on lui tint compte de l'intention saps s'arrter  la valeur des choses. Chaque legs tait d'ailleurs appropri  la personne avec un soin dlicat qui y ajoutait un nouveau prix. Marguerite eut une dernire attention elle laissa son se-crtaire ouvert et plaa sur la tablette la pice qui rendait Ludovic matre de tout rgler chez elle et d'agir  son gr. Prs du testament tait l'anneau, ce triste et mystrieux em-blme. Ds le premier abord les yeux devaient se porter sur ces objets, et le jeune homme y reconnatrait quelles avaient t, au moment de quitter ce monde, la pense de la mou-rante et sa proccupation. Quand elle en eut fini avec la terre, Marguerite songea au ciel elle s'agenouilla devant le portrait de sa grand'mre et pria avec ferveur. Que fut cette prire? Sans doute un acte de contritipp et en mme temps un cri de dsespoir. Elle prit Dieu  tmoin, et, lui montrant l'tat de son me, invo-qua sa misricorde ayec un accent plor. Elle leur demanda d'unir leurs prires  la sienne afin d'en augmenter l'effet et d'ob-tenir ce pardon qui descend d'en haut sur les coeurs humi-lis et sincres. ocr.sentence: the other young man, this his father had received wrong.
ocr.region: 247 OF FRYER BACON. told the other young man, this his father had received wrong. He answered againe, that it was faire. At last there grew such foule words betweenc them, and their bloods were so heated, that they presently stabbed one the other with their daggers, and so fell downe dead. Fryer Bacon seeing them fall, ranne to them, but it was too late, for they were breathlesse ere he came. This made him to grieve exceedingly be iudging that they had received the cause of their deaths by this glasse, tooke the glasse in his hand, aud uttered words to this effect Wretched Bacon, wretched in thy knowledge, in thy understanding wretched for thy art hath beene the ruine of these two gentlemen. Had I been busied in those holy things, the which mine order tyes me to, I had not had that time that made this wicked glasse wicked I weU may cad it, that is the causer of so vde an act would it were sensible, then should it feele my wrath but being as it is, He ruin it for ruining of them and with that he broke his rare and wonderftdl glasse, whose Hke the whole world had not. In this grief of his, came there newes to him of the deaths of Vandermast and Fryer Bungey This did increase his griefe, and made him sorrowfull, that in three days he would not eate any thing but kept his chamber.

He prayed, that God would forgive them both, for so he had no cause, for they had received the cause of their deaths by their owne witnesse.

Now a little to the purpose of this history. For he that was brought in, was called Henry de Montemorel, whom all the world knows. And his death by his owne will was to the following effect: One Sir Edward Byset, Knight, had a sonne, whom he had a wife to, called Alice Fitz Walter, whom he had by her from the time he was in France, who brought him a sonne of her owne. This Sir Edward Byset, and his wife, and sonne were of the Countrie of Salisbury, in England, and Sir Edward was a gentleman of high estate and of great repute, as well for his great knowledge in arms, and his wisdom in warre, as for his great knowledge and worth in the world. He was a very noble and vertuous man, and of great parts and learning. This Sir Edward Byset was a great lover of the learning, and was a man of much charity and good-will, as well to all the scholars in the world, as to all poor people, and all his acquaintance. And he was a most worthy man, and of much good faith and honour, as well as great vertue and honour, who was well-beloved of all men.

This Henry, as I said was one of the servants of this gentleman, and also his owne son

Now a little to the purpose of this history. For he that was brought in, was called Henry de Montemorel, whom all the world knows. And his death by his owne will was to the following effect: One Sir Edward Byset, Knight, had a sonne, whom he had a wife to, called Alice Fitz Walter, whom he had by her from the time he was in France, who brought him a sonne of her owne. This Sir Edward Byset, and his wife, and sonne were of the Countrie of Salisbury, in England, and Sir Edward was a gentleman of high estate and of great repute, as well for his great knowledge in arms, and his wisdom in warre, as for his great knowledge and worth in the world. He was a very noble and vertuous man, and of great parts and learning. This Sir Edward Byset was a great lover of the learning, and was a man of much charity and good-will, as well to all the scholars in the world, as to all poor people, and all his acquaintance. And he was a most worthy man, and of much good faith and honour, as well as great vertue and honour, who was well-beloved of all men.

This Henry, as I said was one of the servants of this gentleman, and also his owne son

ocr.sentence: Fryer Bacon seeing them fall, ranne to them, but it was too late, for they were breathlesse ere he came.
ocr.region: 247 OF FRYER BACON. told the other young man, this his father had received wrong. He answered againe, that it was faire. At last there grew such foule words betweenc them, and their bloods were so heated, that they presently stabbed one the other with their daggers, and so fell downe dead. Fryer Bacon seeing them fall, ranne to them, but it was too late, for they were breathlesse ere he came. This made him to grieve exceedingly be iudging that they had received the cause of their deaths by this glasse, tooke the glasse in his hand, aud uttered words to this effect Wretched Bacon, wretched in thy knowledge, in thy understanding wretched for thy art hath beene the ruine of these two gentlemen. Had I been busied in those holy things, the which mine order tyes me to, I had not had that time that made this wicked glasse wicked I weU may cad it, that is the causer of so vde an act would it were sensible, then should it feele my wrath but being as it is, He ruin it for ruining of them and with that he broke his rare and wonderftdl glasse, whose Hke the whole world had not. In this grief of his, came there newes to him of the deaths of Vandermast and Fryer Bungey This did increase his griefe, and made him sorrowfull, that in three days he would not eate any thing but kept his chamber.

Then said Rush, I thank thee Master, and now I pray thee, I have two or three things that I must doe, that is to saye, I must get a new shirt, for mine is very old and tattered, and I must get two pence for my lodging, for I haue none, and I must buy some good meat, for mine is almost spent and spent, and I must get to the church, for the time is come, that I must worke on my sermon, which I must have by nightfall. Then said the maister Devdle, goe you home, and if any thing is to be done, let it be so done at once. Now as Rush was going he heard a noise of many men making merry in the church, so he went in and saw three or foure olde men, that were very stout, fighting stifly with staves. Then he called unto them, and said, Gentlemen, are you the priore and his curates that so much pleasure themselues in fighting? The priore said, Sir, I am, and these are my curates. Then said Rush, Sir, I pray you be ddigent, and make an end of your fight, for I will not be sauagely breake by you. So then said the priore to his curates, Gentlemen, if hee be an honest man, let him come by us; and if hee be a fauourer, we shall doe him all the wrong, and we will breake him with a stave that I doe carry, and then hee shall be all the better for it. Par le concours des circonstances, j'tais compromise  un point qu'aucune rparation n'tait possible, si ce n'est celle que pouvait m'offrir Melcbior. Son but tait atteint il m'avait mise  la discrtion de son hon-neur. Triste garantie ! et je le vis bien plus tard. Je succombai une barrire s'leva entre vous et moi je ne pouvais plus tre  vous, Ludovic. Les heures s'cou-laient il fallut prendre un parti. Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Nous primes donc, Melchior et moi, nos dernires dis-positions. Au petit jour, et quand la porte fut ouverte, il quitta la maison. Un rendez-vous avait t fix, et je devais aller le rejoindre. Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. -Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. -Qu'ai liez-vous penser de moi? Hlas 1 quoi que vous pussiez en penser, la ralit dpasserait vos suppositions. J'tais une fille dshonore ! XXX - Pourtant, Ludovic, je vous crivis quelques mots, non pas tels que j'aurais voulu les crire, mais assez prcis pour que dsormais vous me regardassiez comme perdue pour vous. Puis j'enlevai de mon doigt l'anneau qui me venait de ma grand'mre et qui avait si mal prserv mon honneur. Je n'tais plus digne de le porter, quoi qu'il arrivt et de quel-que faon que tournassent les choses. Je rejoignis Melchior et le trouvai ivre de son bonheur. Moi-mme,  ce premier moment, j'prouvai ce vertige des sens qui n'est que la fausse monnaie de l'amour. Melchior

The Author of the book of The Famous History or of the Famous and famous men was a man by name of Sir Robert Bacon, who was a great friend of the King, and one of the Judges of the King's Bench. Hee writeth an history of the Kings Maiesty, from the beginning of the world to the end of the world. There are two copies in the Bodleian, one of them being bound up, but not the other, which is a copy printed by Iohn Wynkyn de Worde, which is of a good large size, and very handsomely bound, and not much lesse valuable. The second copy was printed by him in folio. There are three copies in the Cotton Library, one by Wynkyn de Worde, one by Wynkyn de Worde in the forme of a letter, the other by Wynkyn de Worde, who hath a name to bee the first English printer, and hee printed the first English book of any sort that was ever printed, which was the Bible, which was not printed, but written, by John Wycliffe. It is worth note that in both books, and in the printed book of Sir Robert Bacon, where he was the printer, that is to say, it was not printed by him, but written by him, there is a dedication to the King of England, which I shall shew you, that I might bee able to perswade you

Fryer Bacon, to save himselfe from this danger that was like to happen to him would alwayes when that he read, hold a ball of brasse in his hand, and under that ball would hee set a bason of brasse, that if hee did chance to sleepe in his reading, the fall of the ball out of his hand into the bason, might wake him. Being one day in his study in this manner, and asleepe, the Walloon souldier was got in to him, and had drawne his sword to kill him but as hee was ready for to strike, downe fell the ball out of Fryer Bacon's hand, and waked him. Hee seeing the souldier stand there with a sword drawne, asked him what hee was ? and wherefore hee came there in that manner ? The souldier boldly answered him thus I am a Walloon, and a souldier, and more then this, a villaine I am come hither, because I was sent I was sent, because I was hyred I was hyred, because I durst do it the thing I should doe, is not done the thing to be done, is to kill thee thus have you heard what I am and why I came. Fryer Bacon wondered at this man's resolution then asked hee of him, who set him on worke to bee a murderer ? ocr.sentence: Ne t'amuse pas en chemin, car  peu prs cinq cents mtres avant d'arriver, il voltige des bom-bes!
ocr.region: LES TLPHONISTES DANS LA BATAILLE 9 III LA FERME DE BEAUSJOUR L A feuille  la main, le sergent, debout devant l'abri du colonel, faisait la rpartition des postes. - Duruy, dit-il, tu vas monter avec tes hommes au secteur I, tu longeras un peu la route jusqu'aux boyaux B 1 et B 2, au tournant du ruisseau, ils sont perpendiculaires  la Grande Transversale, aprs quoi tu monteras tout droit jus-qu'au poste du commandant. Ne t'amuse pas en chemin, car  peu prs cinq cents mtres avant d'arriver, il voltige des bom-bes!. Legrand, tu prends le secteur H, dangereux pour les marmites, surtout au Bois Equerre tu suivras le boyau central jusqu'au boyau Boscary, o tu trouveras le poste de son com-mandant. Attention vous autres, baissez la tte, les balles tra-versent la route! Je garde deux hommes avec moi au poste du colonel,  da borne 16. La nuit tait venne, pas de lune, une obscurit complte rgnait sur les tranches, et sauf les coups de fusils espacs, partant des premires lignes, la soire tait calme. Les fuses dans le ciel irradiaient par moments l'horizon de leur courbe gracieuse, inondant les parapets d'une lueur blafarde. L'quipe se spara en deux. Puis,  la file, les nouveaux venus longrent la route le plus prs possible du remblai pour viter les balles perdues qui froufroutaient avec un bruit de soie, allant frapper les troncs d'arbres de l'autre ct du ruis-seau. - Pour une belle nuit, c'est une beMe nuit, remarqua R-gnier, un combat de ngres sous un tunnel et  chaque fuse il gouaillait Ah! la belle bleue! - Allez, activez le mouvement, lana Legrand impatient, en laissant derrire lui Duruy qui entrait dans son boyau, nous avons encore un bout de chemin! Sans se dtourner il poursuivit sa marche  ttons, cher-chant  ehaque trou la pancarte indicatrice.

ocr.sentence: CE PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE qu'on PEUT VOIR DANS UNE rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si. peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui ! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, -on puise des mo-tifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant- de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul mais une force imprieuse et presque indpen-dante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers ? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, .comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon coeur Peut-tre, hlas ! en interrogeant mieux ce coeur, aurais-je trouv le dernier mot de ces rticences. La suite ne l'a que trop prouv j'tais dj touche, j'entrais dans cette srie de faiblesses qui m'ont perdue. C'est ici que j'ai besoin de votre pardon, Ludovic, d'un pardon absolu et gnreux. Point d'excuse possible, rien qui puisse pallier ce commen-cement de trahison. Vous aviez t pour moi le meilleur, le plus dvou et le plus fidle des amis vous n'aviez qu'une pense, mon bonheur qu'un but, notre union. Jamais, c'est une justice que je me plais  vous rendre, aucun chagrin ne m'est venu de vous si j'exprimais un dsir, vous vous em-pressiez de le satisfaire si j'avais un ennui, vous vous offriez - le partager. Vous tiez de ces loyaux compagnons qu'une femme est trop heureuse de rencontrer dans sa vie, qui l'as-sistent dans les bons et les mauvais jours et se donnent sans rserve comme sans calcul. Je voyais tout cela, je le sentais et ne mconnaissais point-vos mrites. Lui, au contraire, qu'tait-il et quel fonds pouvais-je -

Yet had Fryer Bacon not revenge enough of them, but bid his man Miles leave them some larger measure as hee thought fitting, which Miles did. Miles straight ledde them out of the house into the fields, they followed him, dauncing after a wilde anticke man-ner then led hee them over a broad dike full of water, and they followed him still, but not so good a way as he went for he went over the bridge, but they by reason of their dauncing, could not keepe the bridge, but fell off, and dauncing through the water then led hee them through a way where a horse might very well have been up to the belly they followed him, and were so durtie, as though they had wallowed in the myre like swine sometime gave hee them rest onely to laugh at them then were they so sleepie when hee did not play, that they fell to the ground. ocr.sentence: he said to Rush, thou lewd fellow, what hast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ?
ocr.region: 277 OF FRIER RUSH. then he said to Rush, thou lew d fellow, what bast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ? Rush answered and said sir, I have done nothing but as you commanded me. That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to makeready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another babite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour caUed for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they caUed for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their

That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to makeready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another babite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour caUed for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they caUed for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their

And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they caUed for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their supper. Then the good man of the house called Rush and said Sir, I pray you make ane end and bring us some more wine. But he answred and said: Sir, I am not able to doe so, for I am very sad, and I hope if I can make you merry, it will cheer me. Then said the good man: You are very welcome, Sir, but I can never make any one merry, for I am no witnesse to no man, nor any power to make any one merry. So the good man went into his chamber, and the other fellowes also, and so they sate in silence, and then they began to discourse how they might get some wine. And when Rush had thought of nothing, but that the Priour had ordered him to annoint the wheeles and axeltrees of the waggon, he remembered how his master, the Knight of St. Ouersea, had given him to eat the best meat he could at his table, and to drink wine the best he could, and to have the best bed he could have at his lodging, and so it happened now, that he remembred that his maister had told him to get the best lodging that he could in the towne. And as he remembered all this, he fell into a good mind, and then said to the other, Why do you not, Master, come with me and get thee a pottle of wine, and then I will go with thee, and we will buy us a pottle of wine together, and come home and have a merry mooing there, and we shall sleep in peace to morrow. So they went with the good man of the house to the winehouse and there they bought a pottle of wine, and then Rush bought himself a shirt, for his maister had given him none but a gaberdine to wear, and a pair of pantaloons, which were very good, and

And when Frier Rush saw that they were fighting together, anon he blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of Hght therein whereby the one might see the other and when he had so done, be tooke his truncheon in his hand, and went into the Quier among the thickest of the Friers the which were fighting freshly without light, and there he laid so lustily about, that many of them he felled to the ground, and left them there for dead, and when he had so done, he stole his way from them, and as hee went, he found standing in the portaU of the Quier, a great olde deske, and anon hee tooke the deske betweene both his hands, and threw it over the portad into the Quier among aU the Friers, and hurt many sore, in so much that some had an arme broken, and some a legge, and other some had their noses, cleane pared from their faces, that the bloud ranne in their mouthes, and as for broken heads to the hard scalpe were no dainty, for every man had one, there scaped none free away, who had been there, should have had a goodly pastime to see the Friers creepe about the Quier, and in steede of Domine labia they cried out alas and well away. Then when the fray was done, and all the noyse seased, Rush came in among them with a candell light in his hand, and made as he had knowne nothing thereof, and said to them Fie for shame sirs, how fortuned this discord to faU among your selves? I see well now you regard not your honour, nor the good name of your house. The good Lord, my Lady and all your honoured family, will hold your fauour. For I will make you a present of this very day one hundred marks of good Goldes. And if you do not come forth with me, I will make you a present of every one of you so long as you will live, fifty pounds sterling. Let it be my pleasure that the Lady and your fauourd sonnes be present at the first marriage, and with all the fauours of my good Lorde my Master. And hee therewithal called two Friers to the table, and made them offer and accept of his present, so that they were both sore affrighted and maruellous. And when he had well made over his part and taken his leave, and had set his feete downe for to goe forth, the Lady was sore abashed, and would not suffer him to depart. And when she had gotten holde of his arm, hee being a stranger and unknown to her, for her great affright she would not suffer him to depart, and by and by hee made as if he had done it. But when she had put her arm away from him, and he had gone out, he ranne to the Lady and kissed her on the cheek, and said withal, your worship I will not be angry with you, but I shall be sure to have my will to make my peace with you, as soon as you come into your honour, and when he had said this, he went his way.

THE MARRIAGE OF HENRY THURLOW AND MARY WARD

But when Frier Rush had so done, he stole his way home again, and then, to make his journey pleasant, hee threw his arms about the neck of a child and said to him: Faire child, I pray thee tell me the name of thy father? and the childe answered: Frier Rush. Then said he: But I pray thee say the name of thy mother? And the childe answered: Maister Wiggily. Then said he: But who art thou then, that hast so much courage to fight against a thousand? And the childe answered: I am Wiggily. Then said hee: Well, childe, thou art a very goodly fellow, and if thou art to have a father in thy time to come, hee will be a very good man, for thy father is a frier, and thou hast a frier's name and frier's armes, and if thou art to have a mother, shee will be a very good woman, for thou hast the mother's name and the mother's armes. But wilt thou tell me, who gave thee the name Wiggily? And the childe answered: Wiggily was given me, because I would not wag my head in the presence of the King.

And hee therewithal called two Friers to the table, and made them offer and accept of his present, so that they were both sore affrighted and maruellous. And when he had well made over his part and taken his leave, and had set his feete downe for to goe forth, the Lady was sore abashed, and would not suffer him to depart. And when she had gotten holde of his arm, hee being a stranger and unknown to her, for her great affright she would not suffer him to depart, and by and by hee made as if he had done it. But when she had put her arm away from him, and he had gone out, he ranne to the Lady and kissed her on the cheek, and said withal, your worship I will not be angry with you, but I shall be sure to have my will to make my peace with you, as soon as you come into your honour, and when he had said this, he went his way.

prediction.sentence:
Ovid, The Metamorphoses, Book XXIII, translated by Alfred J. Smith, with a commentary by John Fiske, trans. (London: J. Murray, 1890), vol. 1, p. 556-757.

The Priour in the above lines is an ancient court official. He may be a personage of great importance in Ovid's original; or he may be a person of more or less minor status.

The Priour's advice to Rush, to apply tar to the axles and wheels of the waggon, might seem strange to our modern mind, unless we knew something of the peculiar dangers that beset medieval waggons, and the methods employed to keep the horses from straying or running away. Waggon accidents were common, and it was not uncommon to see the wheels and axles of a broken-down waggon still littered on the roadside. In some cases, the drivers and passengers had fallen to the ground, to be trampled by the horses, or by each other, or by the wheels themselves. Horses that ran

ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 273 filling their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly. And when Frier Rush had delivered aH his staves, he was right glad in his heart, for he knew right well there should be a great fray among them, either one time or other. So it fortuned afterward, as it is a common cus-tome among religious people at an high feast, to keepe solemne service, and every man to be at Mattens at midnight, and so upon a good night, all the whole Covent assembled together in the Quier, and were ready to begin Mattens, they taried for nothing but for the comming of the Priour. Then anon the Priour came into the Quier, and sate him downe in his place, and as he looked about him, he espied that the Subpriour was there present, and with that his heart began to grudge of the olde anger that was fallen betweene them two, and he thought in his minde that he could never be revenged in a better time, and sodainly he rose out of his place, and went to the Subpriour, and with his fist he gave him a good buffet, and the Subpriour which was moved with the stroke, started unto the Priour and gave him another buffet, and with that they went freshly together by the eares, and when the other Friers saw that, every man rose out of their places, and drew out their Truncheons, and together they went who VOL. I.

ocr.sentence: who fought with the dragon, and killed it Vandermast following his example raysed up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster, and killed it, so were they both released from their danger.
ocr.region: OF FRYER BACON. 243 George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it Vandermast following his example raysed up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster, and kdled it, so were they both released from their danger. They being not contented with this tryall of their skill, went further in their coniurations, and raised up two spirits, each of them one. Bungye charged his spirit for to assist him with the greatest power hee had, that by it he might be able to overcome Vandermast. The Devdl told him he would, if that he from his left arme would give him but three drops of blood but if that he did deny him that, then should Vandermast have power over him to doe what he would the Hke told Vandermasts Devill to him to this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking for to overcome each other but the Devill overthrew them both. They having given the Devill this bloud, as is before spoken of, they both fell againe to their coniurations first, Bungye did rayse Achilles with bis Greekes, who marched about Vandermast and threatned him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Troians, who defended him from AchiUes and the Greekes. Then began there a great batteU between the Greekes and Troians, which continued a good space at last Hector was slaine, and the Troians fled. Then did follow a great tempest, with thundring and lightning, so that the two coniurers wished that they had been away. But wishes were in vaine for now the time was come, that the Devill would be paid for the knowledge that he had

prediction.region: of Bungye and the Devill took AchiUes to his owne country, and in that country he was slaine by a young men sonne of Achilles. The Devill being slaine by his owne sonne, he made such a cry, as did enrage the spirits againe to revenge themselves upon the Devill, so that the Devill was slaine in a manner very like the former occasion, by a sonne of Achilles. So they both fell againe to their coniurations, and began againe to rayse up spirits and fight with them, but now they were slaine in a manner more like the former occasion, by a sonne of Achilles. In this kind of way continued this battle two whole dayes, till in the third day there was a storme and a tempest. The spirits were driven up high in the air, and some of them fell downe in the fields, but many of them were lost in the fields of the war, and in the way. Then the coniurers were all frighted, for if that had been lost in the fields, it had been a shame for them, and had they been caught, they had surely been put to death, but when the coniurers saw their spirits that were gone into the air, they knew that the battle was all lost. The Devill took the place of Bungye, and the Devill told the spirit to doe what hee would, but if that he did not doe it, then should hee have the Devill with the greatest power. The Devill told him he would, if that he from his left arme would give him but three drops of blood but if that he did deny him that, then should Vandermast have power over him to doe what he would the like told Vandermasts Devill to him to this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking for to overcome each other but the Devill overthrew them both. They having given the Devill this bloud, as is before spoken of, they both fell againe to their coniurations first, Bungye did rayse Achilles with his Greekes, who marched about Vandermast and threatned him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Troians, who defended him from Achilles and the Greekes. Then began there a great battell between the Greekes and Troians, which continued a good space at last Hector was slaine, and the Troians fled. Then did follow a great tempest, with thundring and lightning, so that the two coniurers wished that they had been away. But wishes were in vaine for now the time was come, that the Devill would be paid for the knowledge that he had

Then within a while after the Priour came unto the gate and espied Rush the young man standing there ad alone. Anon he said unto him, what dost thou here, and what wouldest thou have.
